<div id="main-article" class="article-content retro-folders">
<p></p><div class="quoteright" style="width:350px;"><div class="lazy_load_img_box" style="padding-top:55.43%"><img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/avonfoundationtrilogy.jpg" class="embeddedimage" border="0" alt="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/avonfoundationtrilogy.jpg" width="350" height="194"></div></div><div class="quoteright" style="width:350px;"><img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/asimov_foundation_trilogy.jpg" class="embeddedimage" border="0" alt="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/asimov_foundation_trilogy.jpg"></div><div class="acaptionright" style="width:350px;"> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IdiosyncraticCoverArt" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IdiosyncraticCoverArt">Idiosyncratic Cover Art</a></div><p></p><div class="indent"><em>"You are a planet suddenly cut off from the still-civilized centers of the Galaxy, and threatened by your stronger neighbors. You are a small world of scientists surrounded by vast and rapidly expanding reaches of barbarism. You are an island of nuclear power in a growing ocean of more primitive energy; but are helpless despite that, because of your lack of metals. You see, then, that you are faced by hard necessity, and that action is forced on you. The nature of that action &mdash; that is, the solution to your dilemma &mdash; is, of course, obvious!"</em><div class="indent">&mdash; <strong>Hari Seldon</strong>, "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists">The Encyclopedists</a>"</div></div><div class="proper-ad-unit mobile-ad square_ad"><h6 class="ad-caption">Advertisement:</h6><div id="proper-ad-tvtropes_mobile_ad_1"><script>propertag.cmd.push(function() { proper_display('tvtropes_mobile_ad_1'); })</script></div></div><p>These <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy">three books</a>, published individually as well as in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BoxedSet" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BoxedSet">Boxed Set</a> and <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> volumes, form the core of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/IsaacAsimov" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/IsaacAsimov">Isaac Asimov</a>'s famous <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpaceOpera" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpaceOpera">Space Opera</a>. <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> is an <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEpic" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEpic">Epic Narrative</a> that was first told in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PulpMagazine" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PulpMagazine">Pulp Magazines</a> during the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GoldenAge" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GoldenAge">Golden Age</a> of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFiction" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFiction">Science Fiction</a>. It describes the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RisingEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RisingEmpire">rise of Terminus</a> as the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower">Second Galactic Empire</a>, the obstacles presented by the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UngovernableGalaxy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UngovernableGalaxy">schisms along the Periphery</a>, the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VestigialEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VestigialEmpire">remnants of the first Galactic Empire</a>, and the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OutsideContextProblem" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OutsideContextProblem">Mule</a>. Additional stories taking place in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheVerse" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheVerse">this setting</a> have been written, forming the <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FoundationSeries" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FoundationSeries">Foundation</a></em> series.</p><p>Dr Asimov wrote a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SelfParody" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SelfParody">Self-Parody</a> about the trilogy, titled "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheFoundationOfSFSuccess" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheFoundationOfSFSuccess">The Foundation of S.F. Success</a>", and other adaptations include a 1970s <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Radio/TheFoundationTrilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Radio/TheFoundationTrilogy">radio dramatisation</a> by <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/TheBBC" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/TheBBC">BBC Radio</a>, accessible from <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Audible" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Audible">Audible</a> and <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Website/InternetArchive" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Website/InternetArchive">Internet Archive</a>. To see more, visit the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Foundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Foundation">multimedia franchise page</a>.</p><hr><div class="proper-ad-unit mobile-ad square_ad"><h6 class="ad-caption">Advertisement:</h6><div id="proper-ad-tvtropes_mobile_ad_2"><script>propertag.cmd.push(function() { proper_display('tvtropes_mobile_ad_2'); })</script></div></div><h2>Works published as <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em>:</h2> <ul><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Foundation1951" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Foundation1951">Foundation (1951)</a></em>:<ul><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians">The Psychohistorians</a>"</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists">The Encyclopedists</a>"</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMayors" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMayors">The Mayors</a>"</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheTraders" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheTraders">The Traders</a>"</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMerchantPrinces" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMerchantPrinces">The Merchant Princes</a>"</li></ul></li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FoundationAndEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FoundationAndEmpire">Foundation and Empire</a></em>:<ul><li> Prologue</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheGeneralFoundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheGeneralFoundation">The General (Foundation)</a>"</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMule" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMule">The Mule</a>"</li></ul></li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SecondFoundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SecondFoundation">Second Foundation</a></em>:<ul><li> Prologue</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SearchByTheMule" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SearchByTheMule">Search by the Mule</a>"</li><li> "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SearchByTheFoundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SearchByTheFoundation">Search By The Foundation</a>"</li></ul></li></ul><hr><h2><em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> provides examples of:</h2><ul><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AgriWorld" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AgriWorld">Agri World</a>: During the time between "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians">The Psychohistorians</a>" and "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheGeneralFoundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheGeneralFoundation">The General (Foundation)</a>", the Imperial Capital of Trantor is a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CityPlanet" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CityPlanet">City Planet</a> that requires the combined output of 20 agricultural worlds to feed its population of 40 billion people. Ironically, between the events of "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheGeneralFoundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheGeneralFoundation">The General (Foundation)</a>" and "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMule" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMule">The Mule</a>", Trantor is sacked. After the Galactic Empire's fall cuts off its supply lines and it ceases to be the center of the galaxy, it starts to turn into a purely agrarian society, except for the Imperial Library <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">where the Second Foundation is ruling the First Foundation from behind the scenes</span>.</li><div class="proper-ad-unit mobile-ad square_ad"><h6 class="ad-caption">Advertisement:</h6><div id="proper-ad-tvtropes_mobile_ad_3"><script>propertag.cmd.push(function() { proper_display('tvtropes_mobile_ad_3'); })</script></div></div><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan">All According to Plan</a>: Despite having died decades to centuries ago, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter">Hari Seldon</a> planned the events of each chapter. Appearing in the "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting">Time Vault</a>", he announces the primary conflict of the story and reassures the people of Terminus that it will be resolved in their favour. His predictions become known as <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan">the Seldon Plan</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BatmanGambit" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BatmanGambit">Batman Gambit</a>: Hari Seldon sets up <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LongGame" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LongGame">centuries worth of plans</a> in advance, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis">using statistics</a>. The actions taken by his Foundation on Terminus are dictated by the starting conditions (conditions that he arranged). Every so often, a "Seldon Crisis" occurs, where there is only one possible action that the Foundation can take, because any other action would result in their destruction. <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SubvertedTrope" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SubvertedTrope">Subverted</a> when it turns out that <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">the Second Foundation he keeps talking about is a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AncientConspiracy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AncientConspiracy">secret organisation he began</a> with the purpose of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/XanatosSpeedChess" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/XanatosSpeedChess">constantly tweaking details</a> of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan">The Plan</a> to force Terminus back onto his predictions if they began to deviate</span>.<div class="indent">"You see, then, that you are faced by hard necessity, and that action is forced on you. The nature of that action &mdash; that is, the solution to your dilemma &mdash; is, of course, obvious!"<em> &mdash; <strong>Hari Seldon</strong>, </em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists">The Encyclopedists</a>"</div></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BenevolentConspiracy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BenevolentConspiracy">Benevolent Conspiracy</a>: The Second Foundation is the opposite of the Foundation on Terminus in many ways; established at "the opposite end of the galaxy", a secret cabal of mentalists rather than a public presence of scientists and engineers, but both are present to prevent thirty thousand years of anarchy that would occur without following <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan">the Seldon Plan</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BilledAboveTheTitle" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BilledAboveTheTitle">Billed Above the Title</a>:<ul><li> The 1963 Science Fiction Book Club copy of <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> printed his name above the title, with "Isaac" in roughly the same size as the title, but with "Asimov" about 50% larger. The full name is underlined and coloured green.</li><li> The <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon">Avon</a> and Equinox cover for <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> from 1974 printed Dr Asimov's name above the title, but at the same size.</li><li> <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe">Bastei Lubbe</a>'s 1983 German translation of <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> (<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MarketBasedTitle" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MarketBasedTitle">changed to</a> <em>Die Psychohistoriker</em>) places Dr Asimov's name in slightly smaller font above the title.</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BoxedSet" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BoxedSet">Boxed Set</a>:<ul><li> <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/GnomePress" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/GnomePress">Gnome Press</a> published a slipcase to fit the original hardcover for all three books to celebrate the printing of <em>Second Foundation</em>. The box uses the art of <em>Foundation</em>'s dust jacket for the sides.</li><li> <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon">Avon</a> published a box set of their editions in the 1970s, using a minimized version of each cover for the slipcase art.</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ClarkesThirdLaw" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ClarkesThirdLaw">Clarke's Third Law</a>: When <em>Foundation</em> begins, the Galactic Empire's <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UsedFuture" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UsedFuture">civilization and technology</a> has already begun to crumble; local systems are losing the scientific expertise necessary for an interstellar society to function and control of the Periphery is quickly lost. Starting from the end of "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists">The Encyclopedists</a>", the people of Terminus begin educating people from the Four Kingdoms in technology, such as nuclear power, radioactive synthetics, and hyperwave relays. However, in order to explain the technology in a way they could understand, Terminus <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScamReligion" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScamReligion">has to couch everything in religious terms</a>, effectively saying <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AWizardDidIt" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AWizardDidIt">The Galactic Spirit Did It</a> to convince the local barbarians that it was safe for human use. When a better educated man is trying to piece through the veil of mysticism created by the gulf of distance, he protests that <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeflectorShields" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeflectorShields">a personal shield</a> is impossible. To which the person he's interrogating drolly points out that their status as "magicians" is not wholly unearned.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Deconstruction" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Deconstruction">Deconstruction</a>: Instead of dashing heroics and swashbuckling, as featured in most <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpaceOpera" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpaceOpera">Space Opera</a> stories, the protagonists use their wits and intelligence to escape their problems. Indeed, in most stories, the individuals themselves are unable to do anything to save the day, but historical forces, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/YouCantFightFate" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/YouCantFightFate">beyond the protagonists' control</a>, resolve the conflicts in their favour anyway.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Doorstopper" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Doorstopper">Doorstopper</a>:<ul><li> The 1963 <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> by <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Doubleday" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Doubleday">Doubleday</a> is over 650 pages long. Most omnibus editions are similarly lengthy.</li><li> The 1966 <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> by <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/SidgwickAndJackson" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/SidgwickAndJackson">Sidgwick And Jackson</a> condensed the page count to about 550 pages without losing any of the story.</li><li> The largest copies are the 939 page German <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> translations by <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Heyne" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Heyne">Heyne</a> in 1991 and 1994.</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DoubleSidedBook" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DoubleSidedBook">Double-Sided Book</a>: <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/AceBooks" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/AceBooks">Ace Books</a> double novel series has D-110; <em><a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/NoWorldOfTheirOwn" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/NoWorldOfTheirOwn">No World Of Their Own</a></em> by <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/PoulAnderson" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/PoulAnderson">Poul Anderson</a> on the front and <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheThousandYearPlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheThousandYearPlan">The 1,000 Year Plan</a>'&#146; by <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/IsaacAsimov" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/IsaacAsimov">Isaac Asimov</a> (the first novel of </em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheFoundationTrilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheFoundationTrilogy">The Foundation Trilogy</a>'') on the back.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DoubleMeaning" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DoubleMeaning">Double Meaning</a>: A deliberate <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/InUniverse" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/InUniverse">In-Universe</a> version is when Hari Seldon admits during <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Foundation1951" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Foundation1951">Foundation (1951)</a></em> that he created two Foundations at 'opposite ends of the galaxy'; one at a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MetalPoorPlanet" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MetalPoorPlanet">remote backwater</a> planet at the edge of the galactic arms called Terminus, and the other at Star's End. During <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FoundationAndEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FoundationAndEmpire">Foundation and Empire</a></em>, characters start trying to discover the location of the Second Foundation that Hari Seldon keeps mentioning. In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SecondFoundation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SecondFoundation">Second Foundation</a></em>, characters use 'the other end of the galaxy' as a clue. Some are doing it spatially (i.e. a planet on the opposite edge of the galaxy), others temporally (i.e. Terminus was the last planet to be settled by that point; by that logic, the Second Foundation must be on the first planet &mdash; <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EarthThatWas" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EarthThatWas">Earth That Was</a>). Some of these suggestions were deliberately misleading ideas by the Second Foundation in order to maintain their secrecy. <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">Hari Seldon meant Trantor, whose <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IstanbulNotConstantinople" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IstanbulNotConstantinople">archaic nickname was Star's End</a>, was at the galactic core (in a spiral, the opposite ends are the centre and the far arms), and was the sociological opposite of Terminus (the centre of galactic business/government versus a remote backwater).</span></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Epigraph" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Epigraph">Epigraph</a>: When these stories were collected into a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Novel" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Novel">Novel</a> format, segments from the <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GreatBigBookOfEverything" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GreatBigBookOfEverything">Encyclopedia Galactica</a></em> were included at the start of each chapter <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EncyclopediaExposita" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EncyclopediaExposita">to give the setting more depth</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Hologram" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Hologram">Hologram</a>: Hari Seldon, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter">near the end of his life</a>, recorded <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting">messages for the future</a>. These messages are built into what the people of Terminus call a "Time Vault", and a three-dimensional recording of Seldon shows up within the cube. These are simple recordings, and Seldon cannot respond to any visual or auditory cues from the audience. He uses these messages to <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan">comment on current events</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IdiosyncraticCoverArt" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IdiosyncraticCoverArt">Idiosyncratic Cover Art</a>: <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Panther" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Panther">Panther</a>'s 1962 covers were illustrated by <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/ChrisFoss" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/ChrisFoss">Chris Foss</a> and they designed a 3-part joiner cover, where laying the books side-to-side form one continuous artwork <a class="urllink" href="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/asimov_foundation_trilogy.jpg">(link)<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a><small>&loz;</small>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LongGame" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LongGame">Long Game</a>: The first story in this <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy">Trilogy</a>, "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians">The Psychohistorians</a>", has Hari Seldon on trial, where he explains his belief that the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower">Galactic Empire</a> will dissolve within the next few centuries, leading to <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TenThousandYears" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TenThousandYears">thirty thousand years of anarchy</a>. The conclusion of the trial allows him to establish a project writing the <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GreatBigBookOfEverything" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GreatBigBookOfEverything">Encyclopedia Galactica</a></em> on Terminus, a planet at the furthest edge of the galaxy. Fifty years later, in "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheEncyclopedists">The Encyclopedists</a>", the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter">long-dead Hari Seldon</a> appears as a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting">recording</a> to announce that the project is a sham, concocted to establish them as <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RisingEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RisingEmpire">the nucleus of a second Galactic Empire</a>. It will take nine hundred fifty more years until they reclaim the entire galaxy, but <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan">even now, they face the first of several Crises that will shape their destiny</a>. Also, there's a second Foundation at the opposite end of the galaxy, which comes into play when someone tries to disrupt <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan">his Plan</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LowCultureHighTech" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LowCultureHighTech">Low Culture, High Tech</a>: One of the factors causing the collapse of the Galactic Empire is, having long become used to complacent peace and prosperity, its scientists have become content to simply preserve and pass down received wisdom rather than creating new inventions or making new discoveries. At the same time, the divide between theoretical and applied science grows to the point that nearly everyone (except for the Foundation itself) loses the ability to maintain their own infrastructure, much less expand it. As early as 25 years after Hari Seldon predicted the fall of the Empire, a nuclear reactor experiences a Chernobyl-like disaster due to lack of understanding, so the Empire's response is to <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LostTechnology" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LostTechnology">restrict the use of nuclear power</a>. The neighboring Four Kingdoms are fighting in spaceships with oil and coal powering them.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MarketBasedTitle" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MarketBasedTitle">Market-Based Title</a>:<ul><li> <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/SidgwickAndJackson" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/SidgwickAndJackson">Sidgwick And Jackson</a> published a version of <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> with the name <em>An Isaac Asimov Omnibus</em> in 1966.</li><li> <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe">Bastei Lubbe</a>'s 1983 German translation of <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> based the title of their volume <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TitleDropChapter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TitleDropChapter">on the first chapter</a>; <em>Die Psychohistoriker</em>.</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NamingYourColonyWorld" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NamingYourColonyWorld">Naming Your Colony World</a>: Since "<a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Foundation1941" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Foundation1941">Foundation 1941</a>", Terminus has been the capital panet of the (First) Foundation. It is given this name because it is the furthest habitable planet from the galactic core, the 'terminus' of the galaxy. It also shares its name with the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Myth/ClassicalMythology" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Myth/ClassicalMythology">Roman god</a> of boundary stones and property disputes.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a>:<ul><li> Multiple publishers have printed this <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy">Trilogy</a> as a single volume, which usually forms a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Doorstopper" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Doorstopper">Doorstopper</a> hardcover book.</li><li> <em>Isaac Asimov</em> is the title for a six-book compilation; <em><a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheStarsLikeDust" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheStarsLikeDust">The Stars Like Dust</a></em>, <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheNakedSun" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheNakedSun">The Naked Sun</a></em>, <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/IRobot" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/IRobot">I, Robot</a></em>, and the three books of <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheFoundationTrilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheFoundationTrilogy">The Foundation Trilogy</a></em>.</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PatchworkStory" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PatchworkStory">Patchwork Story</a>: This <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy">trilogy</a> is made from nine short fiction stories (eight of which were previously published in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PulpMagazine" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PulpMagazine">Pulp Magazines</a>), set <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DistantSequel" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DistantSequel">decades to centuries apart</a>, all patched together into three volumes.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan">The Plan</a>: The Seldon Plan is a very very <em>very</em> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LongGame" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LongGame">long-term plan</a>. The Seldon Plan involves <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheMilkyWayIsTheOnlyWay" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheMilkyWayIsTheOnlyWay">the entire Milky Way galaxy</a>, populated by a few quadrillion people at least, over a period of a millennium, with a dash of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/XanatosSpeedChess" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/XanatosSpeedChess">Xanatos Speed Chess</a> (<span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">The Second Foundation</span>) thrown in to keep the whole thing from going off the rails.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheProphecy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheProphecy">The Prophecy</a>: Hari Seldon <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Seers" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Seers">predicts the future of the galaxy</a> using psychohistory, a set of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis">mathematical formulas that can predict human behaviour</a> (developed by Seldon). He anticipates that the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower">Galactic Empire</a> will collapse and leave the Milky Way in anarchy for <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TenThousandYears" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TenThousandYears">thirty thousand years</a>. To avoid this, he designs <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThePlan">the Seldon Plan</a> to shorten this interval to about <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThousandYearReign" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThousandYearReign">one thousand years</a> instead. It becomes popular knowledge in the galaxy that Seldon's Plan makes the Foundation of Terminus undefeatable.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RecycledInSpace" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RecycledInSpace">Recycled In Space</a>: <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/IsaacAsimov" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/IsaacAsimov">Isaac Asimov</a> was open about his efforts to write a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFiction" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFiction">Science Fiction</a> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEpic" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEpic">saga</a> that was effectively <em><a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheDeclineAndFallOfTheRomanEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheDeclineAndFallOfTheRomanEmpire">The Decline And Fall Of The Roman Empire</a></em> <span class="font-s">IN SPACE</span>! Trantor is the capital of Rome, and the primary perspective is from a planet at the outer edges of the empire, watching as they grow to supplant Trantor as the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GalacticSuperpower">capital of a galactic empire</a>. Several aspects of the collapse are recycled to fit the new setting, such as the Byzantine Empire (Cleon II is Justinian I and Bel Riose is Bellisarius) and the sacking of Rome (Trantor's <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CityPlanet" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CityPlanet">City Planet</a> is torn apart and the capital is moved to Neotrantor).</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScryVsScry" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScryVsScry">Scry vs. Scry</a>: Using psychohistory, the actions of a population and large-scale events that will happen in their future can be predicted with near-perfect precision, barring <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OutsideContextProblem" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OutsideContextProblem">never-before-seen events</a> that throw the entire game out of whack. However, the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis">mathematics underpinning psychohistory</a> depend on the population <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UnspokenPlanGuarantee" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UnspokenPlanGuarantee">being unaware of the predictions</a>, which means conflicts between factions capable of psychohistory need to be resolved with what amounts to old-fashioned <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BattleOfWits" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BattleOfWits">plotting and scheming</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Seers" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Seers">Seers</a>: Everyone who learns psychohistory, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PrescienceByAnalysis">a system of mathematics to predict human behaviour</a>, is capable of analyzing the future and guessing (with a high degree of accuracy) what will happen. Hari Seldon, the one who designed the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FictionalFieldOfScience" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FictionalFieldOfScience">science</a>, was decried as "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEndIsNigh" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEndIsNigh">Raven Seldon</a>". It's not until decades after his death that the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScamReligion" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScamReligion">Scam Religion</a> established by Terminus starts spreading the message of him as a prophet and <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BecauseDestinySaysSo" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BecauseDestinySaysSo">the Foundation's destiny to rule the galaxy</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SerialNovel" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SerialNovel">Serial Novel</a>: Each book in this <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy">Trilogy</a> is comprised of several stories that began as short fiction in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Magazine/AstoundingScienceFiction" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Magazine/AstoundingScienceFiction">Astounding Science Fiction</a></em>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/StrongEmpireShriveledEmperor" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/StrongEmpireShriveledEmperor">Strong Empire, Shriveled Emperor</a>: The Mule is a mutant with enough skill and power to build a huge empire and the ability to brainwash his enemies into being fanatically loyal servants, but with a frail build and enough health problems to die before he's fifty.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Tagline" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Tagline">Tagline</a>:<ul><li> "Three Classics of Science Fiction" &mdash; <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Doubleday" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Doubleday">Doubleday</a> edition of <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> from 1963</li><li> "Winner of The Hugo Award for Best All-Time Series" &mdash; <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon">Avon</a>'s <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BoxedSet" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BoxedSet">Boxed Set</a> from the 1970s</li><li> "Hugo award for best all-time series" and "The classic read by millions" &mdash; <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Avon">Avon</a> and Equinox cover for <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> from 1974</li><li> "Die beruhmte Foundation-Trilogie" &mdash; <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe">Bastei Lubbe</a>'s cover for the German translation of <em>The Foundation Trilogy</em> from 1983</li><li> "The Million-copy Bestseller" &mdash; <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/DelRey" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/DelRey">Del Rey</a>'s cover from 1983</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TitleDropChapter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TitleDropChapter">Title Drop Chapter</a>: The 1983 German <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Omnibus">Omnibus</a> translation of the trilogy by <a class="createlink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/BasteiLubbe">Bastei Lubbe</a> chose to name the volume <em>Die Psychohistoriker</em>, matching the first chapter, "<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ThePsychohistorians">The Psychohistorians</a>".</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UnbuiltTrope" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UnbuiltTrope">Unbuilt Trope</a>: This <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Trilogy">trilogy</a> codified <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheFederation" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheFederation">The Federation</a>, under the name of the "Galactic Empire". The main plot describes the inherent <strong>weakness</strong> of interstellar democracy, and its decay into a corrupted <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEmpire">Empire</a>. While it is one of the formative works of the Golden Age of science fiction, Hari Seldon is neither the archetypal <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ActionHero" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ActionHero">Action Hero</a> or <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceHero" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceHero">Science Hero</a> character, but instead a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GuileHero" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GuileHero">Guile Hero</a> who uses social and political tools against the Foundation's enemies... he dies of old age before the plot begins in earnest, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter">not that it stops him</a> from guiding the development of the next <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HegemonicEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HegemonicEmpire">Hegemonic Empire</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VideoWills" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VideoWills">Video Wills</a>: Hari Seldon, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PosthumousCharacter">near the end of his life</a>, recorded several <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Hologram" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Hologram">holographic messages</a> to be viewed at specific dates in the future, anniversaries of the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FoundingDay" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FoundingDay">founding of Terminus</a>. Unusually for this trope, these <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadManWriting">messages</a> are not about the distribution of his assets, but rather opportunities for him to <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AllAccordingToPlan">comment on current events</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Zeerust" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Zeerust">Zeerust</a>: Society seems to be stuck in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheFifties" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheFifties">The '50s</a> despite the setting being tens of thousands of years in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheFuture" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheFuture">The Future</a>. <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EverybodySmokes" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EverybodySmokes">Everybody Smokes</a>, mobile communication devices don't exist, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RaygunGothic" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RaygunGothic">everything runs on nuclear power</a>, the newspaper print industry is still around, and computer data is stored on microfilm.</li></ul><hr>
</div>
<div class="alt-titles section section-fact">
<h3>
<strong>Alternative Title(s):</strong>
<span>An Isaac Asimov Omnibus</span> </h3>
</div>
